{"title_page": "Bodheswaran", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Bodheshwaran\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| birthname     = Kesava Pilla\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1901|12|28}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1990|7|3|1901|12|28}}\n| death_place   =\n| othername     = \n| occupation    = [[Indian independence activist]], social reformer, poet\n| yearsactive   = \n| parents       = Kunjan Pilla, Janaki Pilla\n| spouse        = V. K. Karthiyani\n| children      = [[:ml:\u0d39\u0d43\u0d26\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3f|Hridayakumari]], [[Sugathakumari]], Sujatha\n}}\n'''Bodheswaran''' (December 28, 1901 \u2013 July 3, 1990), (also known as '''Bodheswarananda'''), was an [[Indian independence activist]], social reformer and a poet of [[Malayalam literature]]. He was known for his nationalistic poems such as ''Keralaganam'' and for his involvement in social movements like [[Vaikom Satyagraha]] and other related events which led to the [[Temple Entry Proclamation]] of 1936.\n\n== Biography ==\nBodheswaran, n\u00e9e Keshava Pilla, was born on December 28, 1901 in [[Neyyattinkara]], in [[Travancore]] (in the present day [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]], India) to Champayil veettil Kunjan Pilla and Thazhamangalam Janaki Pilla.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/Bodeswarangraphy.htm |title=Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |date=2019-04-08 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Influenced by the thoughts of [[Swami Vivekananda]] from an early age, he left his studies to visit the social and religious reformer [[Narayana Guru]] with whom he stayed for about two years.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.veethi.com/india-people/bodheswaran-profile-2024-30.htm |title=Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile |date=2019-04-08 |website=veethi.com |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Subsequently, he travelled throughout India and during a visit to the [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]], he assumed the name of Bodheswarananda. It was during these travels, he met several [[Sannyasins]] and Indian independence activists; he also had the opportunity to attend the public meetings of [[Mohandas K. Gandhi]] and [[Motilal Nehru]].<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-JRfipEdV0C |title=Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography |last=R. Raman |first=Nair |last2=L. Sulochana |first2=Devi |publisher=Centre for South Indian Studies |year=2010 |isbn=978-81-905928-2-6 |location=Trivandrum |pages=168\u2013169 |access-date=2011-10-11}}</ref>\n\nBodheswaran was married to V. K. Karthyayani, a professor of Sanskrit in the [[Government Sanskrit College, Thiruvananthapuram]].<ref name=ThanuLalita1993p399>{{cite book |title=Women Writing in India: The twentieth century |volume=2 |series=Women Writing in India: 600 B.C. to the Present |editor1-first=Susie J. |editor1-last=Tharu |editor2-first=Ke |editor2-last=Lalita |publisher=Feminist Press |year=1993 |page=399 |isbn=978-1-55861-029-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OjZYf9Xf9bcC&pg=PA399 |accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref> The couple had three daughters, [[:ml:\u0d39\u0d43\u0d26\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3f|Hridayakumari]], [[Sugathakumari]] and Sujatha, all the three being noted writers.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\">{{Cite web |url=http://keralaliterature.com/old/author.php?authid=1416 |title=Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature |date=2019-04-08 |website=keralaliterature.com |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"About Author Sujatha Devi\">{{Cite web |url=https://keralabookstore.com/about-author/sujatha-devi/2695/ |title=About Author Sujatha Devi |website=keralabookstore.com |language=en |access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> He died on July 3, 1990, at the age of 88.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" />\n\n==With Chattampi Swamikal and Narayana Guru==\nOn his return to Kerala, Bodheswaran was advised by Narayana Guru to meet [[Chattampi Swamikal]], who was known to have been a major influence in his life.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\" /> Thereafter, he kept his association with Swamikal, while getting involved the [[Indian freedom struggle]] and made several public speeches which were saide to have attracted large crowds.<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" /> After a short spell during which he favoured the [[Arya Samaj]] movement, he got involved in the [[Vaikom Satyagraha]] and other related events until the [[Temple Entry Proclamation]] of 1936.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\" /> He also became a member of the [[Indian National Congress]] and changed his name once more, to Bodheswaran.<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" />\n\nAfter [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] Bodheswaran gradually withdrew from active politics, although he remained a Congressman until his death. He lectured and wrote on the subject of Swamikal, his belief as quoted by Nair and Devi is that Swamikal was \"an embodiment of perfect knowledge\".<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" />\n\n== Legacy and honours ==\nBodheswaran was known for his poems reflecting nationalistic fervour during his involvement in the [[Indian independence movement]] which included ''Keralaganam'', a popular patriotic song of the times.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\" /><ref name=\"Singh2015\">{{cite book|author=Prerna Singh|title=How Solidarity Works for Welfare: Subnationalism and Social Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=229bCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|year=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-07005-9|pages=85\u2013}}</ref> He published six books which, besides poetry anthologies, include a compilation of his speeches.<ref name=\"List of works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/BodeswaranBooks.htm |title=List of works |date=2019-04-08 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> He attempted to write a comprehensive world history covering the period up to [[World War I]] but could not complete it. ''Suprabhatham'', a amagazine he founded, also had only a short life.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" />\n\nThe Government of India honoured him with the ''Thamra Patra'' (Copper Plaque) for his contributions to the Indian independence movement.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" /> His birth centenary was celebrated in 2002 when [[K. R. Narayanan]], the then president of India, inaugurated ''Bodheshwaran Foundation'', an eponymous organization, for propagating his ideals.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran foundation inaugurated - Times of India\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/Bodheswaran-foundation-inaugurated/articleshow/30988422.cms |title=Bodheswaran foundation inaugurated - Times of India |website=The Times of India |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> ''Keralaganam'', his patriotic song, was declared as the cultural song of Kerala in 2014.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Div col}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://mgucat.mgu.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=19545&query_desc=au%252Cwrdl%253A%2520Bodheswaran |title=Thiranhedutha kavithakal (Bodheswaran) |last=Bodheswaran |date=1982}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=217611 |title=Raktha Rekhakal (Pusthakam - 1) |last=Bodheswaran |date=1948 |publisher= |location=}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=49957 |title=Swathanthra Keralam |last=Bodheswaran |date= |publisher= |location=Ernakulam}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=60239 |title=Hrudhayanguram |last=Bodheswaran |date= |publisher= |location=}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=295980 |title=Bodheswarante thiranjedutha kavithakal |last=Bodheswaran |last2=Sugathakumari (editor) |date=2015 |publisher=Priyadarsini |location=Thiruvananthapuram}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* [[List of Malayalam-language authors by category]]\n* [[List of Malayalam-language authors]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal|India|Literature}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA558 |title=The Encyclopaedia Of Indian Literature |volume=1 (A To Devo) |first=Amaresh |last=Datta |publisher=Sahitya Akademi |year=2006 |isbn=978-81-260-1803-1}}\n*{{cite book |title=Thiranjedutha Kavithakal |author=Bodheswaran |location=Kottayam |publisher=DC Books |year=1982}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/poetrytheschool.htm |title=Poetry - The Second Generation of Romantics |publisher=Information & Public Relations Department, Government of Kerala |accessdate=2011-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927043928/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/poetrytheschool.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/Bodeswaran.htm |title=Portrait commissioned by Kerala Sahitya Akademi |date=2019-04-05 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-04-05}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/BodeswaranScript.htm |title=Handwriting |date=2019-04-05 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-04-05}}\n* {{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VZH9zX5D8Fs |title=Jayajaya Komala Kerala - By Jayachandran and Madhuri from National Songs (Album) |last=Devaragangal |date=2010-07-10 |access-date=2019-04-09}}\n\n{{Malayalam Literature |state=collapsed}}\n{{Narayana Guru}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu revivalists]]\n[[Category:People from Thiruvananthapuram district]]\n[[Category:Poets from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Gandhians]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian reformers]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Bodheshwaran\n| image         = \n| caption       =\n| birthname     = Kesava Pilla\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1901|12|28}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1990|7|3|1901|12|28}}\n| death_place   =\n| othername     = \n| occupation    = [[Indian independence activist]], social reformer, poet\n| yearsactive   = \n| parents       = Kunjan Pilla, Janaki Pilla\n| spouse        = V. K. Karthiyani\n| children      = [[:ml:\u0d39\u0d43\u0d26\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3f|Hridayakumari]], [[Sugathakumari]], Sujatha\n}}\n'''Bodheswaran''' (December 28, 1901 \u2013 July 3, 1990), (also known as '''Bodheswarananda'''), was an [[Indian independence activist]], social reformer and a poet of [[Malayalam literature]]. He was known for his nationalistic poems such as ''Keralaganam'' and for his involvement in social movements like [[Vaikom Satyagraha]] and other related events which led to the [[Temple Entry Proclamation]] of 1936.\n\n== Biography ==\nBodheswaran, n\u00e9e Keshava Pilla, was born on December 28, 1901 in [[Neyyattinkara]], in [[Travancore]] (in the present day [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]], India) to Champayil veettil Kunjan Pilla and Thazhamangalam Janaki Pilla.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/Bodeswarangraphy.htm |title=Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |date=2019-04-08 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Influenced by the thoughts of [[Swami Vivekananda]] from an early age, he left his studies to visit the social and religious reformer [[Narayana Guru]] with whom he stayed for about two years.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.veethi.com/india-people/bodheswaran-profile-2024-30.htm |title=Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile |date=2019-04-08 |website=veethi.com |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Subsequently, he travelled throughout India and during a visit to the [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]], he assumed the name of Bodheswarananda. It was during these travels, he met several [[Sannyasins]] and Indian independence activists; he also had the opportunity to attend the public meetings of [[Mohandas K. Gandhi]] and [[Motilal Nehru]].<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-JRfipEdV0C |title=Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography |last=R. Raman |first=Nair |last2=L. Sulochana |first2=Devi |publisher=Centre for South Indian Studies |year=2010 |isbn=978-81-905928-2-6 |location=Trivandrum |pages=168\u2013169 |access-date=2011-10-11}}</ref>\n\nBodheswaran was married to V. K. Karthyayani, a professor of Sanskrit in the [[Government Sanskrit College, Thiruvananthapuram]].<ref name=ThanuLalita1993p399>{{cite book |title=Women Writing in India: The twentieth century |volume=2 |series=Women Writing in India: 600 B.C. to the Present |editor1-first=Susie J. |editor1-last=Tharu |editor2-first=Ke |editor2-last=Lalita |publisher=Feminist Press |year=1993 |page=399 |isbn=978-1-55861-029-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OjZYf9Xf9bcC&pg=PA399 |accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref> The couple had three daughters, [[:ml:\u0d39\u0d43\u0d26\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d3f|Hridayakumari]], [[Sugathakumari]] and Sujatha, all the three being noted writers.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\">{{Cite web |url=http://keralaliterature.com/old/author.php?authid=1416 |title=Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature |date=2019-04-08 |website=keralaliterature.com |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"About Author Sujatha Devi\">{{Cite web |url=https://keralabookstore.com/about-author/sujatha-devi/2695/ |title=About Author Sujatha Devi |website=keralabookstore.com |language=en |access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> He died on July 3, 1990, at the age of 88.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" />\n\n==With Chattampi Swamikal and Narayana Guru==\nOn his return to Kerala, Bodheswaran was advised by Narayana Guru to meet [[Chattampi Swamikal]], who was known to have been a major influence in his life.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\" /> Thereafter, he kept his association with Swamikal, while getting involved the [[Indian freedom struggle]] and made several public speeches which were saide to have attracted large crowds.<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" /> After a short spell during which he favoured the [[Arya Samaj]] movement, he got involved in the [[Vaikom Satyagraha]] and other related events until the [[Temple Entry Proclamation]] of 1936.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran -  Veethi profile\" /> He also became a member of the [[Indian National Congress]] and changed his name once more, to Bodheswaran.<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" />\n\nAfter [[Partition of India|Indian independence]] Bodheswaran gradually withdrew from active politics, although he remained a Congressman until his death. He lectured and wrote on the subject of Swamikal, his belief as quoted by Nair and Devi is that Swamikal was \"an embodiment of perfect knowledge\".<ref name=\"Chattampi Swami: An Intellectual Biography\" />\n\n== Legacy and honours ==\nBodheswaran was known for his poems reflecting nationalistic fervour during his involvement in the [[Indian independence movement]] which included ''Keralaganam'', a popular patriotic song of the times.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\" /><ref name=\"Singh2015\">{{cite book|author=Prerna Singh|title=How Solidarity Works for Welfare: Subnationalism and Social Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=229bCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|year=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-07005-9|pages=85\u2013}}</ref> He published six books which, besides poetry anthologies, include a compilation of his speeches.<ref name=\"List of works\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaakademi.org/sp/Writers/PROFILES/Bodeswaran/Html/BodeswaranBooks.htm |title=List of works |date=2019-04-08 |website=Kerala Sahitya Akademi |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> He attempted to write a comprehensive world history covering the period up to [[World War I]] but could not complete it. ''Suprabhatham'', a amagazine he founded, also had only a short life.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" />\n\nThe Government of India honoured him with the ''Thamra Patra'' (Copper Plaque) for his contributions to the Indian independence movement.<ref name=\"Biography on Kerala Sahitya Akademi portal\" /> His birth centenary was celebrated in 2002 when [[K. R. Narayanan]], the then president of India, inaugurated ''Bodheshwaran Foundation'', an eponymous organization, for propagating his ideals.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran foundation inaugurated - Times of India\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/Bodheswaran-foundation-inaugurated/articleshow/30988422.cms |title=Bodheswaran foundation inaugurated - Times of India |website=The Times of India |access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> ''Keralaganam'', his patriotic song, was declared as the cultural song of Kerala in 2014.<ref name=\"Bodheswaran - Kerala Literature\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Div col}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://mgucat.mgu.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=19545&query_desc=au%252Cwrdl%253A%2520Bodheswaran |title=Thiranhedutha kavithakal (Bodheswaran) |last=Bodheswaran |date=1982}}\n* {{Cite book |url=https://catalog.uoc.ac.in/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=217611 |title=Raktha Rekhakal (Pusthakam - 1) |last=Bodheswaran |date=1948 |publisher= |location=}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=49957 |title=Swathanthra Keralam |last=Bodheswaran |date= |publisher= |location=Ernakulam}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=60239 |title=Hrudhayanguram |last=Bodheswaran |date= |publisher= |location=}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://103.251.43.202:8080/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=295980 |title=Bodheswarante thiranjedutha kavithakal |last=Bodheswaran |last2=Sugathakumari (editor) |date=2015 |publisher=Priyadarsini |location=Thiruvananthapuram}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* [[List of Malayalam-language authors by category]]\n* [[List of Malayalam-language authors]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal|India|Literature}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA558 |title=The Encyclopaedia Of Indian Literature |volume=1 (A To Devo) |first=Amaresh |last=Datta |publisher=Sahitya Akademi |year=2006 |isbn=978-81-260-1803-1}}\n*{{cite book |title=Thiranjedutha Kavithakal |author=Bodheswaran |location=Kottayam |publisher=DC Books |year=1982}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/poetrytheschool.htm |title=Poetry - The Second Generation of Romantics |publisher=Information & Public Relations Department, Government of Kerala |accessdate=2011-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927043928/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/poetrytheschool.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.keralasahityaak